Now pretty reliably you
can go to Baja California,

00:47:35.064 --> 00:47:38.450
you can go off Cancun, you
could go a hundred miles south

00:47:38.450 --> 00:47:41.850
of the Mississippi Delta,
out into the Gulf of Mexico,

00:47:41.850 --> 00:47:43.210
and find yourself in the midst

00:47:43.210 --> 00:47:47.700
of gaggles of whale sharks feeding.

00:47:47.700 --> 00:47:49.720
You have to first of all
find out where the food is

00:47:49.720 --> 00:47:50.930
and then you're likely to find out

00:47:50.930 --> 00:47:52.736
where the whale sharks gather.

00:47:52.736 --> 00:47:54.869
And off the west coast of Australia

00:47:54.869 --> 00:47:58.019
at certain times of the year,
whale sharks get together.

00:47:58.019 --> 00:48:01.163
And mostly they're solitary,
but when there's food around

00:48:01.163 --> 00:48:04.510
nobody knows yet where
they go to whoop it up

00:48:04.510 --> 00:48:06.900
and do what it takes to
make more whale sharks,

00:48:06.900 --> 00:48:08.635
the breeding areas, still a mystery.

00:48:08.635 --> 00:48:12.024
But one thing we do know is that

00:48:12.024 --> 00:48:15.139
when they take a big gulp of plankton,

00:48:15.139 --> 00:48:19.148
they're taking a gulp of a
cross-section of life on earth.

00:48:19.148 --> 00:48:22.450
The larval stages of so many
of the creatures in the sea,

00:48:22.450 --> 00:48:25.597
maybe a dozen phyla of
animals go down the guzzle

00:48:25.597 --> 00:48:28.377
of a whale shark with every gulp.

00:48:28.377 --> 00:48:32.170
It's astonishing the diversity
of life that's out there

00:48:32.170 --> 00:48:33.659
in the water itself.

00:48:33.659 --> 00:48:37.840
So when they put a desal
plant in and take in water,

00:48:37.840 --> 00:48:38.780
it isn't just water.

00:48:38.780 --> 00:48:41.218
It's a soup, it's a living soup.

00:48:41.218 --> 00:48:43.877
You sacrifice all the little
guys that are in the water

00:48:43.877 --> 00:48:48.500
going in to get fresh water and salt

00:48:48.500 --> 00:48:49.570
coming out the other end,

00:48:49.570 --> 00:48:52.130
and that doesn't mean that
we shouldn't be doing this,

00:48:52.130 --> 00:48:54.397
but we should do it with our eyes open,

00:48:54.397 --> 00:48:56.650
and consider the trade-offs.

00:48:56.650 --> 00:49:00.940
Be careful and maybe get
smarter about how we deal

00:49:00.940 --> 00:49:03.313
with water as a commodity,

00:49:05.600 --> 00:49:08.050
and fish as a commodity.

00:49:08.050 --> 00:49:11.920
Huh, living underwater,
that first experience,

00:49:11.920 --> 00:49:13.870
and every time since, and now every dive,

00:49:13.870 --> 00:49:15.820
every time I put my face
in the water I'm aware

00:49:15.820 --> 00:49:18.990
that every fish is different
from every other one,

00:49:18.990 --> 00:49:21.540
and if a fish came sailing
through this room right now

00:49:21.540 --> 00:49:22.910
and looked around, they'd probably think

00:49:22.910 --> 00:49:26.363
that all people look alike,
and that's the attitude

00:49:26.363 --> 00:49:30.660
that I had about sardines, or grouper,

00:49:30.660 --> 00:49:32.620
or even you know squid.

00:49:32.620 --> 00:49:34.913
You see a big flock of
them, a group of them

00:49:34.913 --> 00:49:37.530
and they do look pretty much alike,

00:49:37.530 --> 00:49:39.860
and then when you spend time with them,

00:49:39.860 --> 00:49:42.630
quality time, like day and
night, get to know individuals.

00:49:42.630 --> 00:49:45.510
You realize they have different faces,

00:49:45.510 --> 00:49:47.870
different behaviors, different attitudes.

00:49:47.870 --> 00:49:49.590
You can tell them apart.

00:49:49.590 --> 00:49:53.820
Every person on the planet,
whoever has been, is now,

00:49:53.820 --> 00:49:55.140
or ever will be is different.

00:49:55.140 --> 00:49:58.956
Every cat, every dog, I
know it about every cat.

00:49:58.956 --> 00:50:03.200
You know for sure, but it's such a,

00:50:03.200 --> 00:50:05.890
I mean why is it taking
us so long to realize

00:50:05.890 --> 00:50:09.620
that every sardine is its own self,

00:50:09.620 --> 00:50:11.263
different from every other one,

00:50:11.263 --> 00:50:14.192
with its own little DNA fingerprint.

00:50:14.192 --> 00:50:19.192
It's a revelation, coupled with
a revelation new in my time,

00:50:20.012 --> 00:50:24.910
that the connectivity, the DNA, the RNA,

00:50:24.910 --> 00:50:27.407
the chemistry of life
through all forms of life

00:50:27.407 --> 00:50:30.210
is remarkably similar.

00:50:30.210 --> 00:50:32.980
That each of us shares so much in common

00:50:32.980 --> 00:50:36.705
with every cat, every pine
tree, every jellyfish.

00:50:36.705 --> 00:50:39.512
That's the miracle of life.

00:50:39.512 --> 00:50:41.895
The great diversity, infinite diversity,

00:50:41.895 --> 00:50:45.533
and a great common ground we all share.

00:50:46.490 --> 00:50:48.960
That puts us as part of the system.

00:50:48.960 --> 00:50:50.053
It's all connected.

00:50:51.520 --> 00:50:54.190
No two parrot fish that look exactly alike

00:50:54.190 --> 00:50:57.490
with freckles on their
nose, or speckled rays,

00:50:57.490 --> 00:51:01.210
or spotted little trunk
fish, or angel fish,

00:51:01.210 --> 00:51:02.883
of you name it.

00:51:03.733 --> 00:51:06.101
Now we know.

00:51:06.101 --> 00:51:10.636
Now that we know there's no excuse anymore

00:51:10.636 --> 00:51:13.453
for continuing to behave toward the ocean

00:51:13.453 --> 00:51:18.453
as if it's just a place to take
stuff out and put things in.

00:51:18.736 --> 00:51:23.670
We need to understand and
respect the ocean with new eyes,

00:51:23.670 --> 00:51:25.370
new understanding, and new policies,

00:51:25.370 --> 00:51:28.797
new ways that are not
just good for the fish

00:51:28.797 --> 00:51:32.470
and the reefs of the ocean,
the whales and whatever,

00:51:32.470 --> 00:51:34.379
but it's really important to us.

00:51:34.379 --> 00:51:39.379
So extracting wildlife
from the sea using trawls

00:51:40.300 --> 00:51:42.009
that scrape the sea floor

00:51:42.009 --> 00:51:46.559
like bulldozers catching
songbirds using, in a forest.

00:51:46.559 --> 00:51:50.310
Scrape them up and shake out
the forest, throw it away,

00:51:50.310 --> 00:51:52.144
and take a few pounds of protein.

00:51:52.144 --> 00:51:57.144
We're destroying much of the
ocean with these heavy duty

00:51:57.280 --> 00:52:00.611
damaging techniques that 50 years ago,

00:52:00.611 --> 00:52:03.365
40 years ago, even 25 years ago,

00:52:03.365 --> 00:52:06.350
maybe there was some excuse
because we didn't know

00:52:06.350 --> 00:52:09.530
what we now know, how
vulnerable the ocean is

00:52:09.530 --> 00:52:11.228
to our actions.

00:52:11.228 --> 00:52:15.850
You know I love the policies
that have been developed

00:52:15.850 --> 00:52:20.479
over recent times to look
at Mars, our sister planet,

00:52:20.479 --> 00:52:23.230
and other places, and
thinking about what we can do

00:52:23.230 --> 00:52:26.720
to terraform other parts
of the solar system,

00:52:26.720 --> 00:52:30.260
especially Mars, and yet
you look in our back yard

00:52:30.260 --> 00:52:33.717
and we're kind of doing the reverse.

00:52:33.717 --> 00:52:38.717
We're not, I mean while we're
looking to terraform Mars,

00:52:38.810 --> 00:52:41.852
make it more earthlike,
we're Marsiforming earth,

00:52:41.852 --> 00:52:46.440
making it more, well
making it less hospitable,

00:52:46.440 --> 00:52:48.710
more like our sister planet

00:52:48.710 --> 00:52:51.530
through transformation
of the carpet of life

00:52:51.530 --> 00:52:55.570
that keeps us alive into something that,

00:52:55.570 --> 00:52:57.680
yeah it's okay to farm.

00:52:57.680 --> 00:53:00.033
We need to do that to grow the food.

00:53:00.908 --> 00:53:02.910
In 1800 it was a billion.

00:53:02.910 --> 00:53:04.424
When I came along it was two billion,

00:53:04.424 --> 00:53:07.310
1980, four billion,
now it's seven billion,

00:53:07.310 --> 00:53:08.143
and the numbers go up

00:53:08.143 --> 00:53:10.340
but the planet doesn't get any bigger.

00:53:10.340 --> 00:53:13.790
But we can't just do to the entire planet

00:53:13.790 --> 00:53:15.605
what we've done to a big chunk of it,

00:53:15.605 --> 00:53:19.644
transform the natural
systems that keep us alive,

00:53:19.644 --> 00:53:21.010
into something else.

00:53:21.010 --> 00:53:24.080
We need to get better,
smarter, more efficient,

00:53:24.080 --> 00:53:27.570
more effective about using the assets,

00:53:27.570 --> 00:53:30.309
instead of burning
through the assets as if

00:53:30.309 --> 00:53:32.263
it's all about us, all about now,

00:53:32.263 --> 00:53:36.293
if we want to have a future for humankind.

