and therefore modify coral reefs.

00:59:25.224 --> 00:59:30.224
And last year, this time last year,

00:59:31.424 --> 00:59:34.346
I think many of us were
riveted with what was happening

00:59:34.346 --> 00:59:39.346
in the Gulf of Mexico with
the access to deep sea

00:59:39.400 --> 00:59:41.740
that didn't exist until fairly recently,

00:59:41.740 --> 00:59:45.060
to extract from the heart of the earth,

00:59:45.060 --> 00:59:46.482
beneath the bottom of the ocean,

00:59:46.482 --> 00:59:49.539
far beneath the bottom of the ocean,

00:59:49.539 --> 00:59:51.818
a mile of water, but then
there's the rock beneath,

00:59:51.818 --> 00:59:56.818
to access these sources of power, fuel,

00:59:59.900 --> 01:00:04.130
that we now are using
to power our society,

01:00:04.130 --> 01:00:07.021
and the downside that we are now putting

01:00:07.021 --> 01:00:09.071
on the balance sheet.

01:00:09.071 --> 01:00:11.827
There are risks, there are rewards,

01:00:11.827 --> 01:00:14.438
but certainly there is the big reward

01:00:14.438 --> 01:00:17.172
of using our power, now that we know,

01:00:17.172 --> 01:00:20.670
to shape the future

01:00:20.670 --> 01:00:24.077
based on knowing for example,
that one-time-use plastics

01:00:24.077 --> 01:00:28.920
are kind of a stupid thing
for us to be engaged in

01:00:28.920 --> 01:00:30.420
and yet we are doing it,

01:00:30.420 --> 01:00:32.429
now that we know we
should change our ways.

01:00:32.429 --> 01:00:36.650
This is a good news story,
because that little turtle

01:00:36.650 --> 01:00:40.200
was freed from its
encumbrance and swam away.

01:00:40.200 --> 01:00:41.910
I hope it's still out there.

01:00:41.910 --> 01:00:43.992
But a lot of gear is
out there in the ocean,

01:00:43.992 --> 01:00:47.954
continuing to fish,
continuing to catch and kill

01:00:47.954 --> 01:00:51.920
some 300,000 marine mammals alone,

01:00:51.920 --> 01:00:54.380
and hundreds of thousands
of birds are snared

01:00:54.380 --> 01:00:57.673
in derelict fishing gear every year.

01:00:58.990 --> 01:01:01.520
It's not just entanglement,
it's just the sheer mass

01:01:01.520 --> 01:01:04.714
of the junk that is clogging the ocean.

01:01:04.714 --> 01:01:06.720
This is another good news story.

01:01:06.720 --> 01:01:09.490
Volunteers, students going out

01:01:09.490 --> 01:01:11.020
to the Northwest Hawaiian Islands,

01:01:11.020 --> 01:01:15.343
hoping to retrieve masses of
plastic, the fishing gear,

01:01:15.343 --> 01:01:17.830
and taking it out of the ocean.

01:01:17.830 --> 01:01:20.380
Another good news story,
in July of this year

01:01:20.380 --> 01:01:24.270
I went to Hong Kong where
a thousand school kids

01:01:24.270 --> 01:01:25.938
gathered to take the pledge.

01:01:25.938 --> 01:01:28.205
We will protect sharks.

01:01:28.205 --> 01:01:32.950
We will never eat shark
fin soup again or ever.

01:01:32.950 --> 01:01:34.780
I don't think most of
them ever had tried it,

01:01:34.780 --> 01:01:36.537
but they pledged not to.

01:01:36.537 --> 01:01:40.186
Here in California, just a week ago,

01:01:40.186 --> 01:01:43.980
Governor Brown signed a
legislation making it illegal

01:01:43.980 --> 01:01:47.529
to have trade in shark fins, yahoo, yeah!

01:01:47.529 --> 01:01:51.335
(audience applauding)

01:01:51.335 --> 01:01:53.997
The good news, people do care,

01:01:53.997 --> 01:01:58.886
and that's why I am a hope-aholic.

01:01:58.886 --> 01:02:01.527
I think that armed with knowledge,

01:02:01.527 --> 01:02:03.614
the ability to communicate together,

01:02:03.614 --> 01:02:05.710
and disseminate information,

01:02:05.710 --> 01:02:07.710
and to bring the community together,

01:02:07.710 --> 01:02:10.541
not just the scientists,
not just the policy makers,

01:02:10.541 --> 01:02:14.240
not just the artists,
not just the historians,

01:02:14.240 --> 01:02:16.865
not just the writers, it's everybody.

01:02:16.865 --> 01:02:20.180
I personally have a vested
interest in all of this

01:02:20.180 --> 01:02:21.900
because I have three children.

01:02:21.900 --> 01:02:25.103
I have four grandsons, two of them here,

01:02:25.103 --> 01:02:27.700
and they remind me, we've gotta figure out

01:02:27.700 --> 01:02:29.189
which way are we going, you know.

01:02:29.189 --> 01:02:33.413
We have a choice, we do have a choice.

01:02:33.413 --> 01:02:36.363
What do you like, the
blue one or the red one?

01:02:37.980 --> 01:02:39.960
I like the blue.

01:02:39.960 --> 01:02:43.180
We're edging toward the
red through our actions,

01:02:43.180 --> 01:02:45.912
more CO2 in the
atmosphere, more like mars,

01:02:45.912 --> 01:02:50.912
less water or water that is
not usable for us, less life.

01:02:51.977 --> 01:02:56.977
We want to, I think, aim for this,

01:02:57.130 --> 01:03:00.640
an enduring place for
ourselves within the systems

01:03:00.640 --> 01:03:01.480
that keep us alive.

01:03:01.480 --> 01:03:06.347
Well the consequence of my TED wish,

01:03:06.347 --> 01:03:10.853
I showed this picture first
and I used the comment

01:03:10.853 --> 01:03:14.888
that I first used when I
gave a talk at the World Bank

01:03:14.888 --> 01:03:16.160
a couple years ago.

01:03:16.160 --> 01:03:19.786
I said, there it is, the world bank.

01:03:19.786 --> 01:03:22.253
That's where the assets are,

01:03:22.253 --> 01:03:25.166
and we've been drawing them down

01:03:25.166 --> 01:03:28.232
through the history of our species.

01:03:28.232 --> 01:03:31.643
Now we know, we gotta
take care of the place.

01:03:31.643 --> 01:03:34.780
We have to use those assets wisely.

01:03:34.780 --> 01:03:37.820
It doesn't mean that
we have to stop fishing

01:03:37.820 --> 01:03:42.820
or stop farming in places,
but we can be much wiser

01:03:43.580 --> 01:03:45.407
about how we use the assets.

01:03:45.407 --> 01:03:49.558
We must think about the importance
of the diversity of life

01:03:49.558 --> 01:03:52.457
and its value to us.

01:03:52.457 --> 01:03:56.804
I mean it's good enough for
me to save whales, or tunas,

01:03:56.804 --> 01:04:01.804
or calamari in the, the
squids for their own sake,

01:04:02.410 --> 01:04:03.998
for just because.

01:04:03.998 --> 01:04:05.599
I don't know how to make them

01:04:05.599 --> 01:04:10.450
and I don't think I should
exert my power to destroy them.

01:04:10.450 --> 01:04:15.450
But I think the thing that
will get to most people is

01:04:16.570 --> 01:04:19.146
well what does it matter,
why should I care?

01:04:19.146 --> 01:04:21.320
If the ocean dried up tomorrow,

01:04:21.320 --> 01:04:22.300
what difference would it make?

01:04:22.300 --> 01:04:25.924
Well a lot of difference,
like if you like to breathe,

01:04:25.924 --> 01:04:29.401
if you like to have an existence on earth.

01:04:29.401 --> 01:04:33.980
So, one of the outcomes of
my talk, after the talk,

01:04:33.980 --> 01:04:38.343
right after the talk, one guy came up.

01:04:38.343 --> 01:04:43.343
He was just like a
little, almost elf-like.

01:04:45.190 --> 01:04:49.416
He's just a really
unassuming looking person,

01:04:49.416 --> 01:04:53.603
but he said with a great seriousness.

01:04:54.571 --> 01:04:56.650
I think I understand.

01:04:56.650 --> 01:05:01.650
If we fail to take care of the
ocean, nothing else matters.

01:05:02.541 --> 01:05:05.932
The economy, security,
health, all anchors back

01:05:05.932 --> 01:05:10.554
to taking care of the
natural world, mostly blue.

01:05:10.554 --> 01:05:13.621
And he wrote a check
for a million dollars,

01:05:13.621 --> 01:05:17.560
and that was the start of
Mission Blue as an organization.

01:05:17.560 --> 01:05:21.420
It was the start of an expedition
to the Galapagos Islands

01:05:21.420 --> 01:05:24.076
that took place a year and a half ago,

01:05:24.076 --> 01:05:27.920
where we got about a hundred of people,

01:05:27.920 --> 01:05:30.700
some of the best minds
that we could muster

01:05:30.700 --> 01:05:32.208
from around the world to come together

01:05:32.208 --> 01:05:36.360
and to give the talk of
their life. (laughing)

01:05:36.360 --> 01:05:38.430
About 25 people actually gave talks,

01:05:38.430 --> 01:05:39.711
the rest were there to listen

01:05:39.711 --> 01:05:44.034
and to use what they were inspired to do,

01:05:44.034 --> 01:05:46.770
as a consequence of hearing these talks,

01:05:46.770 --> 01:05:48.340
and thinking about the ocean,

01:05:48.340 --> 01:05:52.060
and to go forth and do something.

01:05:52.060 --> 01:05:55.240
And it's resulted in a
lot of different things,

01:05:55.240 --> 01:05:58.870
but it includes this organization that,

01:05:58.870 --> 01:06:00.600
it's called the Sylvia Earle Alliance,

01:06:00.600 --> 01:06:03.411
but it's a bit like Lance Armstrong.

01:06:03.411 --> 01:06:05.370
That's the foundation.

01:06:05.370 --> 01:06:08.070
But what is he trying to do?

01:06:08.070 --> 01:06:09.330
Livestrong.

01:06:09.330 --> 01:06:11.899
So it's the Sylvia Earle
Alliance, that's the foundation.

01:06:11.899 --> 01:06:13.660
What we're tryin' to do

01:06:13.660 --> 01:06:17.640
is to just build momentum
of the Mission Blue.

01:06:17.640 --> 01:06:19.760
It's to get people to use their talents,

01:06:19.760 --> 01:06:24.297
use their capacity in whatever
way they are inspired to do,

01:06:24.297 --> 01:06:27.110
to make a difference for the ocean.

01:06:27.110 --> 01:06:31.430
It's a loose network of
organizations, of individuals,

01:06:31.430 --> 01:06:34.611
of anybody, everybody
to sign up to the idea

01:06:34.611 --> 01:06:38.129
that it's our mission to
take care of the place.

01:06:38.129 --> 01:06:42.439
And poets can join in,
scientists can do it, kids,

01:06:42.439 --> 01:06:46.550
CEO's, presidents of companies,

01:06:46.550 --> 01:06:49.483
or corporations, or countries.

01:06:49.483 --> 01:06:52.790
Anybody and everyone
can do what they can do.

01:06:52.790 --> 01:06:55.950
I want to just share
with you a little glimpse

01:06:55.950 --> 01:06:57.970
of what happened when we went to sea.

01:06:57.970 --> 01:06:59.334
It's a little video clip.

01:06:59.334 --> 01:07:02.443
It's a trailer actually for
a film that will come out,

01:07:02.443 --> 01:07:05.000
first at Sundance this Spring,

01:07:05.000 --> 01:07:08.034
and then it will be in
theaters I hope following that.

01:07:08.034 --> 01:07:13.034
It's a little heavy on what
they say about Sylvia Earle.

01:07:13.670 --> 01:07:15.050
They should say more about the ocean,

01:07:15.050 --> 01:07:16.863
but it's a glimpse anyway of,

01:07:16.863 --> 01:07:20.264
to catch the idea of
what actually happened.

01:07:20.264 --> 01:07:23.514
(gentle droning music)

01:07:27.600 --> 01:07:28.630
50 years ago

01:07:28.630 --> 01:07:30.270
when I began exploring the ocean,

01:07:30.270 --> 01:07:33.403
it seemed at that time
to be a sea of Eden,

01:07:34.789 --> 01:07:36.570
but now we know.

01:07:36.570 --> 01:07:39.253
We are now facing paradise lost.

01:07:40.760 --> 01:07:43.510
- This trip is absolutely
brand new for TED,

01:07:43.510 --> 01:07:45.556
we've never done anything like it before.

01:07:45.556 --> 01:07:49.240
The trip came about because of a wish

01:07:49.240 --> 01:07:51.670
that TED granted Sylvia Earle.

01:07:51.670 --> 01:07:56.670
- I hope for your help to explore
and protect the wild ocean

01:07:56.740 --> 01:07:58.638
in ways that will restore the health,

01:07:58.638 --> 01:08:03.638
and in so doing secure hope for humankind.

01:08:04.270 --> 01:08:07.000
- Sylvia Earle has devoted her life

01:08:07.000 --> 01:08:09.230
to this passion of the oceans.

01:08:09.230 --> 01:08:11.730
- And the need for
knowledge about all aspects

01:08:11.730 --> 01:08:14.523
of the environment, whether
on the land or on the sea.

01:08:16.290 --> 01:08:17.606
I've always been a scientist.

01:08:17.606 --> 01:08:20.821
I am a scientist, but I've
been transformed in part

01:08:20.821 --> 01:08:22.790
I suppose by having children

01:08:22.790 --> 01:08:26.181
and seeing that the
places I knew as a child,

01:08:26.181 --> 01:08:29.687
I can't take them, because they're gone.

01:08:30.930 --> 01:08:33.870
- [Chris] Trip is a bet,
that if you bring together

01:08:33.870 --> 01:08:37.240
a group of really remarkable
people who are well resourced,

01:08:37.240 --> 01:08:39.778
some of the world's
greatest marine scientists,

01:08:39.778 --> 01:08:42.440
some of the world's great storytellers.

01:08:42.440 --> 01:08:44.649
You put them together and you show them

01:08:44.649 --> 01:08:47.025
what's happening in the oceans,

01:08:47.025 --> 01:08:49.950
something incredible is gonna happen.

01:08:49.950 --> 01:08:54.370
(dramatic orchestral music)

01:08:54.370 --> 01:08:57.450
- I was raised with a
great respect for nature,

01:08:57.450 --> 01:09:00.390
but I'd never added the ocean to that.

01:09:00.390 --> 01:09:04.100
And to be able to be in a
place like the Galapagos,

01:09:04.100 --> 01:09:07.500
to actually get into the water
and see some of the creatures

01:09:07.500 --> 01:09:09.753
that we're talking about
has changed my life.

01:09:10.780 --> 01:09:14.440
- Getting people to not only
understand intellectually,

01:09:14.440 --> 01:09:16.286
but to know their hearts.

01:09:16.286 --> 01:09:19.403
We're so changing the way the world works

01:09:19.403 --> 01:09:21.590
that our future is at risk.

01:09:21.590 --> 01:09:23.429
- The type of fishing going on today

01:09:23.429 --> 01:09:27.780
is really wiping bluefin
ecologically off the planet.

01:09:27.780 --> 01:09:29.670
- Whale meat being sold in these markets

01:09:29.670 --> 01:09:32.530
was really dolphin meat and it was toxic.

01:09:32.530 --> 01:09:35.505
- There's around a hundred
million sharks caught every year,

01:09:35.505 --> 01:09:39.230
so this is a truly global problem.

01:09:39.230 --> 01:09:41.450
- We're literally sucking like a straw,

01:09:41.450 --> 01:09:43.317
life right out of this planet.

01:09:43.317 --> 01:09:45.550
- And so the idea of Hope Spots,

01:09:45.550 --> 01:09:48.740
the idea of protected areas
is like whoa, you know.

01:09:48.740 --> 01:09:51.100
But it's gotta be big,
and it's gotta be real,

01:09:51.100 --> 01:09:53.206
and you gotta have people
with guns out there

01:09:53.206 --> 01:09:55.540
to protect it, because it sure as hell

01:09:55.540 --> 01:09:58.640
isn't gonna be protected
by wishful thinking

01:09:58.640 --> 01:10:01.284
or let's all go off and sing Kum ba yah.

01:10:01.284 --> 01:10:04.660
(dramatic orchestral music)

01:10:04.660 --> 01:10:07.138
- But if wait another 50 years
or even another 10 years,

01:10:07.138 --> 01:10:10.076
things we can do now will be gone.

01:10:10.076 --> 01:10:15.076
- There is no more tomorrow
that we can avoid confronting.

01:10:19.262 --> 01:10:21.060
- [Newscaster] Bobby Jindal has declared

01:10:21.060 --> 01:10:23.535
a state of emergency because of the spill.

01:10:23.535 --> 01:10:25.570
- [Man] What's at stake
for the environment

01:10:25.570 --> 01:10:27.330
is the oil begins to touch land.

01:10:27.330 --> 01:10:32.093
- And to me, crude oil
ain't nuttin' but the devil.

01:10:34.020 --> 01:10:36.320
- Man is destroyin' the planet.

01:10:36.320 --> 01:10:39.330
- Just like the Bible
says, in greed and time

01:10:39.330 --> 01:10:40.930
you will destroy your own earth,

01:10:40.930 --> 01:10:42.773
and that's what's happenin'.

01:10:42.773 --> 01:10:46.200
- Scientists in Mississippi
are trying to gauge the impact

01:10:46.200 --> 01:10:49.360
of the spill as it starts to
spread into the prime habitat

01:10:49.360 --> 01:10:51.323
of the biggest fish in the gulf.

01:10:54.980 --> 01:10:57.190
- These animals are here
to feed during this time

01:10:57.190 --> 01:10:59.050
and this oil spill is
right in their backyard.

01:10:59.050 --> 01:11:01.825
- But they're on death row.

01:11:01.825 --> 01:11:06.073
If for nothing else good
comes of this major spill,

01:11:06.073 --> 01:11:08.510
it may be to wake up people to say

01:11:08.510 --> 01:11:10.670
we have to protect the Gulf.

01:11:10.670 --> 01:11:15.670
- [Man] There are real issues
here of money, and power.

01:11:15.732 --> 01:11:19.120
- It's life itself that
the ocean is delivering

01:11:19.120 --> 01:11:21.310
and we have been abusing the ocean.

01:11:21.310 --> 01:11:23.860
We haven't been caring for the ocean.

01:11:23.860 --> 01:11:26.572
- Why don't we write to
a hundred world leaders?

01:11:26.572 --> 01:11:30.650
- There must be someplace
where these forests

01:11:30.650 --> 01:11:32.910
of unique creatures can be safe.

01:11:32.910 --> 01:11:35.290
- [Man] And Sylvia's timing is
perfect, this is that moment.

01:11:35.290 --> 01:11:37.423
- The government is onboard.

01:11:38.920 --> 01:11:40.300
- And this bill is not only,

01:11:40.300 --> 01:11:42.060
we've heard it's the first
in the United States,

01:11:42.060 --> 01:11:43.610
this is the first in the world.

01:11:45.597 --> 01:11:47.290
- [Sylvia] We're a hundred miles offshore

01:11:47.290 --> 01:11:48.453
in the Gulf of Mexico.

01:11:49.540 --> 01:11:53.707
- On corals, you're just
looking at brown gunky stuff.

01:11:53.707 --> 01:11:56.860
- [Sylvia] A great grand
finale for this version

01:11:56.860 --> 01:12:00.680
of the Alvin, we need every bit

01:12:00.680 --> 01:12:04.236
of insight that we can muster.

01:12:04.236 --> 01:12:07.736
(dramatic rhythmic music)

01:12:10.840 --> 01:12:12.910
The ocean is alive.

01:12:12.910 --> 01:12:16.863
Without the ocean, life on
earth simply would not exist.

01:12:17.910 --> 01:12:21.500
- [Woman] I do not wanna envision a world

01:12:21.500 --> 01:12:23.731
for our grandchildren
and great-grandchildren

01:12:23.731 --> 01:12:25.960
that doesn't have Orcas,

01:12:25.960 --> 01:12:28.310
that doesn't have hammerhead sharks,

01:12:28.310 --> 01:12:29.803
because we're all connected.

01:12:31.150 --> 01:12:32.910
- [Scientist] I'm here
because Sylvia Earle

01:12:32.910 --> 01:12:34.780
is one of the most
remarkable women on earth.

01:12:34.780 --> 01:12:36.750
- [Man] She's the real thing.

01:12:36.750 --> 01:12:39.360
She's a person who has committed herself

01:12:39.360 --> 01:12:42.250
and everything that
that commitment implies,

01:12:42.250 --> 01:12:44.600
and we need more of that.

01:12:44.600 --> 01:12:47.530
- We have the capacity
to protect the systems

01:12:47.530 --> 01:12:48.713
that keep us alive.

01:12:52.180 --> 01:12:54.793
We still have a chance,
but now's the time.

01:13:01.310 --> 01:13:03.593
So this is the time, thank you.

01:13:04.648 --> 01:13:07.815
(audience applauding)

01:13:09.204 --> 01:13:10.317
- [Chris] Hi my name is Chris Pensetitch,

01:13:10.317 --> 01:13:13.316
and I work at the Turtle
Island Restoration Network.

01:13:13.316 --> 01:13:14.149
- Great.

01:13:15.170 --> 01:13:18.720
- [Chris] So there's a group
of people that live very close

01:13:18.720 --> 01:13:21.129
to the ocean, that care
very deeply about the ocean,

01:13:21.129 --> 01:13:26.129
that drag giant bulldozers
across the Gulf of Mexico,

01:13:26.200 --> 01:13:28.339
sweeping down everything in their path,

01:13:28.339 --> 01:13:30.917
the shrimp trawl fishermen.

01:13:30.917 --> 01:13:35.917
How do we communicate to
them that this livelihood

01:13:36.200 --> 01:13:39.420
that they care so much about is something

01:13:39.420 --> 01:13:43.950
that is while profitable,
causing huge devastation

01:13:43.950 --> 01:13:46.693
to the Gulf of Mexico ecosystem?

01:13:46.693 --> 01:13:50.133
- It's a tough question but,

01:13:51.970 --> 01:13:55.720
one answer that I wish
I could snap my fingers

01:13:55.720 --> 01:13:57.160
and make happen is to take them down

01:13:57.160 --> 01:13:58.948
to see what it's like.

01:13:58.948 --> 01:14:03.948
It's transformative, actually
out there in the Gulf where,

01:14:06.050 --> 01:14:10.040
what I was, with the whale
sharks, diving with them,

01:14:10.040 --> 01:14:12.950
it was actually a charter fishing boat.

01:14:12.950 --> 01:14:17.820
This was just sports fishing,
but the crew consisted

01:14:17.820 --> 01:14:20.441
of individuals who were
commercial fishermen,

01:14:20.441 --> 01:14:25.441
and the one, when he saw
us jumping in the water,

01:14:26.509 --> 01:14:28.240
getting the,

01:14:28.240 --> 01:14:30.810
he wasn't intending to
get in the water with me,

01:14:30.810 --> 01:14:32.490
but he couldn't resist it.

01:14:32.490 --> 01:14:36.500
So he jumped in, grabbed
a pair of fins and snorkel

01:14:36.500 --> 01:14:38.789
and he went in the water, and,

01:14:38.789 --> 01:14:43.110
the filmmakers involved
interviewed him afterwards,

01:14:43.110 --> 01:14:46.030
I hope this comes through in
the final cut of the film.

01:14:46.030 --> 01:14:51.030
Because he just gets this
faraway look in his face

01:14:51.090 --> 01:14:53.990
and he talks about how
he thought he could hear

01:14:53.990 --> 01:14:56.797
the heart beating of this big fish,

01:14:56.797 --> 01:15:00.400
and he'd never been in the
water with the fish before,

01:15:00.400 --> 01:15:01.450
never done it.

01:15:01.450 --> 01:15:05.110
But we were all doing it and
the big fish were right there.

01:15:05.110 --> 01:15:06.452
He just couldn't stand it.

01:15:06.452 --> 01:15:09.155
If I had a submarine available

01:15:09.155 --> 01:15:13.374
to take people down to just look.

01:15:13.374 --> 01:15:16.475
People who eat the shrimp
are a part of the problem.

01:15:16.475 --> 01:15:20.270
You love popcorn shrimp,
give it up. (laughing)

01:15:20.270 --> 01:15:24.310
Shrimp cocktail, it's too
expensive no matter how little

01:15:24.310 --> 01:15:26.389
or how much you pay for it.

01:15:26.389 --> 01:15:27.980
The real price of it

01:15:27.980 --> 01:15:30.410
is just not there for you to see.

01:15:30.410 --> 01:15:31.689
It's written in the,

01:15:31.689 --> 01:15:33.992
Monterey Aquarium had a wonderful exhibit,

01:15:33.992 --> 01:15:38.170
not now but recently,
it was a few years ago.

01:15:38.170 --> 01:15:41.730
They had this portrayal
of a crystal goblet

01:15:41.730 --> 01:15:45.430
with shrimp, like a half dozen shrimp,

01:15:45.430 --> 01:15:48.748
big juicy ones all around,
and around it was this halo

01:15:48.748 --> 01:15:52.989
of life that had been
killed in the process

01:15:52.989 --> 01:15:55.180
of getting those six shrimp.

01:15:55.180 --> 01:16:00.180
I mean the ratio is
conservatively five to one.

01:16:00.299 --> 01:16:02.836
I've been onboard shrimp boats,

01:16:02.836 --> 01:16:07.080
it's more like a hundred
to one, sometimes more.

01:16:07.080 --> 01:16:09.607
If you've seen Forrest Gump, (laughing)

01:16:09.607 --> 01:16:12.565
here's the trawler, goes
across the ocean floor,

01:16:12.565 --> 01:16:15.880
Brook dumps it out on the deck,

01:16:15.880 --> 01:16:16.960
turtles included.

01:16:16.960 --> 01:16:18.430
I didn't see any in Forrest Gump,

01:16:18.430 --> 01:16:20.126
but that's how a lot of turtles die,

01:16:20.126 --> 01:16:22.494
or the nets that are left,

01:16:22.494 --> 01:16:26.460
some of the turtles are
drowned because the trawls

01:16:26.460 --> 01:16:27.588
drag for quite a while on the bottom,

01:16:27.588 --> 01:16:30.260
long enough to drown the turtles.

01:16:30.260 --> 01:16:35.260
Anyway, it's just disgraceful
that we know this exists

01:16:36.161 --> 01:16:39.085
and we just go on business as usual.

01:16:39.085 --> 01:16:42.201
Long lines, another great
source of killing turtles.

01:16:42.201 --> 01:16:46.765
Knowing is got to be the answer.

01:16:46.765 --> 01:16:51.250
It's the key, if you
don't know you can't care,

01:16:51.250 --> 01:16:53.300
and most of those who are in the business,

01:16:53.300 --> 01:16:58.300
especially the large-scale,
industrial-scale extraction

01:16:58.312 --> 01:17:02.080
of ocean wildlife, like
menhaden from the Gulf of Mexico

01:17:02.080 --> 01:17:05.980
and the Chesapeake Bay, and
along the Eastern Seaboard.

01:17:05.980 --> 01:17:10.808
It's the filtration
system for those areas,

01:17:10.808 --> 01:17:15.100
along with sponges, and
oysters, and clams, and such,

01:17:15.100 --> 01:17:16.890
and it's part of the food chain.

01:17:16.890 --> 01:17:18.746
It's part of what makes the ocean work.

01:17:18.746 --> 01:17:21.290
And we can get away with taking a few,

01:17:21.290 --> 01:17:23.860
but we can't do it on
the scale that we're now,

01:17:23.860 --> 01:17:26.651
or using the techniques
that we're now imposing.

01:17:26.651 --> 01:17:30.710
So I don't know a straight
answer to your question.

01:17:30.710 --> 01:17:32.410
Short question, he did his job,

01:17:32.410 --> 01:17:34.036
long answer, sorry about that.

01:17:34.036 --> 01:17:37.270
But it takes some real thinking

01:17:37.270 --> 01:17:38.672
and ideas that you might have.

01:17:38.672 --> 01:17:41.903
It's not the fisherman's fault.

01:17:41.903 --> 01:17:44.353
They thought when they started,

01:17:44.353 --> 01:17:46.610
hey this is what we do.

01:17:46.610 --> 01:17:49.230
Nobody thought that there was any problem

01:17:49.230 --> 01:17:51.670
with killing all these starfish,

01:17:51.670 --> 01:17:55.767
and other things that are
dragged up from the ocean floor.

01:17:55.767 --> 01:17:57.570
But the fishermen do know,

01:17:57.570 --> 01:17:59.635
you know I did spend some time,

01:17:59.635 --> 01:18:01.960
I spent a lot of time around the Gulf

01:18:01.960 --> 01:18:04.527
and just a few weeks ago I
was up in Martha's Vineyard,

01:18:04.527 --> 01:18:08.078
the center of the universe
for early whaling.

01:18:08.078 --> 01:18:11.130
You know they've seen the transition.

01:18:11.130 --> 01:18:14.592
Whaling, cod, and now
you know, but they're,

01:18:14.592 --> 01:18:17.302
I think small scale local fishing,

01:18:17.302 --> 01:18:22.302
sensitive to having an enduring place

01:18:22.610 --> 01:18:25.328
within the system could work, might work,

01:18:25.328 --> 01:18:27.930
but whatever it is has to be coupled

01:18:27.930 --> 01:18:29.850
with large-scale protected areas

01:18:29.850 --> 01:18:31.710
where you leave the system alone.

01:18:31.710 --> 01:18:32.617
If you want to have birds,

01:18:32.617 --> 01:18:36.820
you can't just slaughter
them on a wholesale basis.

01:18:36.820 --> 01:18:39.280
We did that with passenger pigeons,

01:18:39.280 --> 01:18:44.280
and the Carolina parakeets,
and Eskimo curlews.

01:18:44.990 --> 01:18:47.759
We know how to exterminate the
great aux, we've done that.

01:18:47.759 --> 01:18:52.040
What we don't have clearly a vision for,

01:18:52.040 --> 01:18:55.510
is how do we keep these
creatures as a part

01:18:55.510 --> 01:18:57.950
of what keeps us alive.

01:18:57.950 --> 01:19:01.229
We need to start at the earliest age

01:19:01.229 --> 01:19:06.229
to get kids locked in to
that as a mission in life.

01:19:06.847 --> 01:19:08.667
The fishermen in the Gulf,

01:19:08.667 --> 01:19:12.820
the kids aren't looking to that as a way

01:19:12.820 --> 01:19:16.479
to make a living, they're not.

01:19:16.479 --> 01:19:18.963
They can't, it's not much of a living now.

01:19:19.975 --> 01:19:22.460
- [Ed] Ed Almanzo with
Laguna Ocean Foundation.

01:19:22.460 --> 01:19:24.270
I wonder if you might say something

01:19:24.270 --> 01:19:27.373
about how these Hope Spots are selected.

01:19:28.455 --> 01:19:31.275
- How are the Hope Spots selected?

01:19:31.275 --> 01:19:36.275
Well, it's like open
season for Hope Spots.

01:19:36.384 --> 01:19:41.384
A colleague of mine, a
fellow explorer in residence

01:19:41.400 --> 01:19:43.522
at the National Geographic, Enric Sala,

01:19:43.522 --> 01:19:45.779
who was at Scripps for 10 years,

01:19:45.779 --> 01:19:50.390
and really focused on
pristine areas to protect.

01:19:50.390 --> 01:19:52.900
And I really whole heartedly endorse that,

01:19:52.900 --> 01:19:55.834
find those places that
are still in great shape

01:19:55.834 --> 01:19:59.770
and do everything you can to
not let them be destroyed,

01:19:59.770 --> 01:20:03.869
like Raja Ampat out in
the Western Pacific,

01:20:03.869 --> 01:20:06.040
like the Northwest Hawaiian Islands

01:20:06.040 --> 01:20:08.254
still in pretty good shape.

01:20:08.254 --> 01:20:13.160
Looking at the deep
reefs almost everywhere,

01:20:13.160 --> 01:20:16.450
in the high seas, there's
still reason for hope

01:20:16.450 --> 01:20:20.290
that if we act now we can
maintain the integrity,

01:20:20.290 --> 01:20:23.428
and they'll help restore some of the areas

01:20:23.428 --> 01:20:25.340
that have been diminished.

01:20:25.340 --> 01:20:28.190
So using the new techniques
that are out there,

01:20:28.190 --> 01:20:32.008
high-diversity is one
measure, water quality.

01:20:32.008 --> 01:20:35.668
Another measure is how realistic is it?

01:20:35.668 --> 01:20:38.070
Is there any possibility

01:20:38.070 --> 01:20:40.300
that you can actually make this happen?

01:20:40.300 --> 01:20:42.130
Good news, just last year,

01:20:42.130 --> 01:20:43.849
this year, this year, earlier this year,

01:20:43.849 --> 01:20:48.849
the UK has declared the
biggest fully protected area

01:20:49.550 --> 01:20:51.830
in the ocean, half a
million square kilometers

01:20:51.830 --> 01:20:55.280
around the Chagos Archipelago
in the Indian Ocean.

01:20:55.280 --> 01:20:57.846
Beautiful coral reefs, no fishing allowed.

01:20:57.846 --> 01:21:01.333
I have a small sea story

01:21:01.333 --> 01:21:03.700
about the Northwest Hawaiian Islands,

01:21:03.700 --> 01:21:08.355
about how that was selected,
took about 10 years of people

01:21:08.355 --> 01:21:12.910
building a database, making
a case for why this matters.

01:21:12.910 --> 01:21:17.147
There's the monk seal,
that's their primary habitat,

01:21:17.147 --> 01:21:18.940
and there are only about a thousand

01:21:18.940 --> 01:21:20.960
of them left in the world.

01:21:20.960 --> 01:21:22.900
So either you take action to protect them

01:21:22.900 --> 01:21:25.298
or we gonna see them go
the way of the monk seal

01:21:25.298 --> 01:21:28.347
that was in the Gulf of
Mexico and the Caribbean.

01:21:28.347 --> 01:21:32.937
The last one seen in 1952,
they're gone, all gone.

01:21:32.937 --> 01:21:37.937
So Jean-Michel Cousteau did a film

01:21:38.940 --> 01:21:40.510
about the Northwest Hawaiian Islands,

01:21:40.510 --> 01:21:42.440
a series of films actually, four films,

01:21:42.440 --> 01:21:47.087
and Laura Bush, a unlikely
person one might think,

01:21:47.087 --> 01:21:49.631
but she does really care about nature

01:21:49.631 --> 01:21:52.701
and she made a trip out to
the Northwest Hawaiian Islands

01:21:52.701 --> 01:21:56.783
to Midway, was just appalled at the mass

01:21:56.783 --> 01:21:59.850
of plastic out there, seeing
those poor albatrosses

01:21:59.850 --> 01:22:04.850
just stuffed, the babies
dead, plastic spilled out

01:22:05.940 --> 01:22:07.146
all over the ground.

01:22:07.146 --> 01:22:10.970
So one thing led to another
and she invited Jean-Michel

01:22:10.970 --> 01:22:13.352
to come to the White
House and show his film.

01:22:13.352 --> 01:22:17.780
And a little list of 50
people were selected,

01:22:17.780 --> 01:22:19.944
I got to be one of the
lucky ducks to be invited,

01:22:19.944 --> 01:22:22.722
and nobody really expected

01:22:22.722 --> 01:22:25.170
that she would show up, but she did,

01:22:25.170 --> 01:22:28.431
and more then that, so did George.

01:22:28.431 --> 01:22:31.930
And must have been a
quiet week in Washington

01:22:31.930 --> 01:22:33.877
or on the planet as a whole,
because they both came,

01:22:33.877 --> 01:22:38.440
and we watched the film,
had popcorn, drank sodas,

01:22:38.440 --> 01:22:41.578
and then we're invited to dinner
in a room about this large

01:22:41.578 --> 01:22:44.893
with tables for six people, and each of,

01:22:44.893 --> 01:22:46.190
they all set up.

01:22:46.190 --> 01:22:47.990
We went through a line to fill our plates

01:22:47.990 --> 01:22:52.024
and I had invited a guest who sat,

01:22:52.024 --> 01:22:53.880
it was a little ahead of me in the line,

01:22:53.880 --> 01:22:56.610
she sat at the table, and
this guy came and asked

01:22:56.610 --> 01:22:57.560
if he could sit next to her

01:22:57.560 --> 01:22:59.853
and it was the President
of the United States.

01:22:59.853 --> 01:23:02.460
And so she said yes he could sit with her,

01:23:02.460 --> 01:23:07.460
and then Jean-Michel
came and sat next to him,

01:23:07.540 --> 01:23:08.660
that was his rightful place,

01:23:08.660 --> 01:23:10.629
and then the head of the
Marine Sanctuary Program,

01:23:10.629 --> 01:23:15.350
Lori Arguelles, Foundation,
and her husband.

01:23:15.350 --> 01:23:16.910
And there's one seat left

01:23:16.910 --> 01:23:19.891
and I started walking toward my friend,

01:23:19.891 --> 01:23:21.470
and then I saw who she was with,

01:23:21.470 --> 01:23:23.441
and then started to back
off 'cause I didn't think,

01:23:23.441 --> 01:23:25.707
you know, I'm just a guest here.

01:23:25.707 --> 01:23:28.691
This is, but my feet kept going anyway

01:23:28.691 --> 01:23:33.691
and I took my place and
we had an hour and a half

01:23:35.085 --> 01:23:40.070
over dinner, without any
watchers or anything.

01:23:40.070 --> 01:23:42.207
We just, we talked fish.

01:23:42.207 --> 01:23:43.520
And I remember hearing myself saying,

01:23:43.520 --> 01:23:45.933
because Bush likes to fish,

01:23:45.933 --> 01:23:48.896
that if there are to be fishermen,

01:23:48.896 --> 01:23:52.173
you've gotta have fish, duh.

01:23:53.096 --> 01:23:55.353
And if you are to have
fish you have to protect

01:23:55.353 --> 01:23:59.080
the places that they live,
breeding areas, feeding areas.

01:23:59.080 --> 01:24:00.398
They have to have space.

01:24:00.398 --> 01:24:04.060
We can't take them anywhere
in any numbers at any time,

01:24:04.060 --> 01:24:06.050
and that's what we've been
doing to fish, and that's why.

01:24:06.050 --> 01:24:09.610
He didn't know that 90% of
many of the big fish are gone.

01:24:09.610 --> 01:24:12.124
He didn't know that less
then 1% of the ocean

01:24:12.124 --> 01:24:16.220
was really protected, at that
time it was less then 1%.

01:24:16.220 --> 01:24:21.003
Because of the 10 years
invested in making a case,

01:24:21.003 --> 01:24:26.003
and people, individuals and
organizations making a case,

01:24:26.071 --> 01:24:30.877
it was kind of an easy nudge,
but it was still unexpected,

01:24:30.877 --> 01:24:35.313
that when he left that night,
he called over to the group,

01:24:35.313 --> 01:24:39.267
to Jim Connaughton, who's
the head of the CEQ,

01:24:39.267 --> 01:24:41.707
"Jim, I want you to make it happen.

01:24:41.707 --> 01:24:44.430
"This should be the biggest area",

01:24:44.430 --> 01:24:46.530
they had three sizes,
small, medium, and large,

01:24:46.530 --> 01:24:48.827
he said, "We want the biggest
area and want it to be

01:24:48.827 --> 01:24:50.391
"no take, no fishing.

01:24:50.391 --> 01:24:52.452
"You got that Jim?"

01:24:52.452 --> 01:24:54.440
Everybody was swept away.

01:24:54.440 --> 01:24:56.010
We thought it was going
to be another place

01:24:56.010 --> 01:24:58.410
like the Monterey Bay Marine Sanctuary

01:24:58.410 --> 01:25:00.022
that is a managed area.

01:25:00.022 --> 01:25:02.653
Where fishing would be fine, you just,

01:25:02.653 --> 01:25:05.240
you know you declare it a sanctuary,

01:25:05.240 --> 01:25:08.180
but you let things go on
pretty much business as usual,

01:25:08.180 --> 01:25:11.050
with some constraints,
and certainly the idea

01:25:11.050 --> 01:25:13.450
that you would educate
people to care for the place,

01:25:13.450 --> 01:25:16.538
but no he said no take.

01:25:16.538 --> 01:25:19.447
To make it happen, meant Jim Connaughton

01:25:19.447 --> 01:25:24.447
went off in a huddle and
resurrected the technique

01:25:24.550 --> 01:25:26.280
that Teddy Roosevelt used to establish

01:25:26.280 --> 01:25:31.280
some of the biggest and best
National Parks in the country,

01:25:32.102 --> 01:25:37.102
and that is the Antiquities
Act that made it possible

01:25:37.830 --> 01:25:40.790
to declare a monument,
that isn't a sanctuary,

01:25:40.790 --> 01:25:42.110
it's a monument.

01:25:42.110 --> 01:25:45.912
So the President by
Presidential decree could say,

01:25:45.912 --> 01:25:50.912
it's 240,000, no it's 340,000
square miles of ocean.

01:25:54.398 --> 01:25:56.147
I'm sorry for the
Northwest Hawaiian Islands,

01:25:56.147 --> 01:25:59.500
140,000 square miles of ocean,

01:25:59.500 --> 01:26:02.401
at the time the biggest marine
protected area in the world

01:26:02.401 --> 01:26:07.401
by the not so green President,
he's certainly blue.

01:26:07.480 --> 01:26:10.170
Because the Northwest Hawaiian Islands

01:26:10.170 --> 01:26:13.210
Marine National Monument is bigger

01:26:13.210 --> 01:26:15.900
then all the National Parks put together,

01:26:15.900 --> 01:26:17.520
and the fish are safe there.

01:26:17.520 --> 01:26:18.901
It takes some enforcement,

01:26:18.901 --> 01:26:20.647
as Jeremy Jackson said, you know,

01:26:20.647 --> 01:26:22.429
"You gotta go out there with guns."

01:26:22.429 --> 01:26:26.902
And there are some problems,
but the fact is that

01:26:26.902 --> 01:26:31.902
that started this big is somethin',

01:26:32.200 --> 01:26:35.600
and in Kiribati in the Western Pacific,

01:26:35.600 --> 01:26:38.000
they have 200 miles surrounding

01:26:38.000 --> 01:26:39.443
their little speck of islands.

01:26:39.443 --> 01:26:44.443
They've established even a
larger marine protected area

01:26:44.458 --> 01:26:48.270
and then came the UK with
the Chagos Archipelago,

01:26:48.270 --> 01:26:50.720
and then Chile, again Enric Sala

01:26:50.720 --> 01:26:52.875
had something to do with this,

01:26:52.875 --> 01:26:55.109
a little speck of rock in the
ocean called Salas y Gomez,

01:26:55.109 --> 01:26:58.500
that now is fully protected
in the waters around it,

01:26:58.500 --> 01:27:00.370
one of the biggest marine protected areas.

01:27:00.370 --> 01:27:01.780
So the needle is moving.

01:27:01.780 --> 01:27:05.375
It was less then 1% and now
it's slightly more then 1%,

01:27:05.375 --> 01:27:07.250
and now there are people who are saying

01:27:07.250 --> 01:27:10.720
we need 20% by 2020, woo-hoo.

01:27:10.720 --> 01:27:12.216
You know, maybe we can get there.

01:27:12.216 --> 01:27:16.415
I don't know, any, every
inch, every drop counts,

01:27:16.415 --> 01:27:18.923
and that's how you do it, any way you can.

01:27:20.500 --> 01:27:22.201
- [William] Please join
me in thanking Dr. Earle

01:27:22.201 --> 01:27:24.889
for a wonderful, informative presentation.

01:27:24.889 --> 01:27:28.056
(audience applauding)

01:27:29.666 --> 01:27:31.416
- [Sylvia] Thank you.

